**a.** The market value of the firm refers to how much total debt and equity the firm is using for their assets. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{V}_L&=\text{V}_U+\text{T}\times\text{D}
\end{aligned}$$

Where, 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{V}_L&=\text{Leveraged value of firm}\\
\text{V}_U&=\text{Value of unlevered firm}\\
\text{T}&=\text{Tax rate}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Debt}
\end{aligned}$$

**b.** Before we construct the balance sheet for the company, we must first solve for the total equity of the firm. To do this, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equity}&=\text{V}_L-\text{D}
\end{aligned}$$

Where.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{V}_L&=\text{Value of unlevered firm}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Debt}
\end{aligned}$$

In order to get the price per share of the company's stock, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price per share}&=\dfrac{\text{Total equity}}{\text{Shares outstanding}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Price per share}&=\dfrac{\$258,579,902}{8,000,000}\\[15 pt]
&=\$32.3225
\end{aligned}$$

The price per share of the company's common stock is $\$32.3225$
